{"title_page": "Delta Police Department", "text_new": "{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n|agencyname      = Delta Police Department\n|logo            = [[File:DPD Crest Small.png|DPD Crest Small]]\n|logocaption     = Badge of the Delta Police Department (DPD)\n|motto           = Honour, Integrity, Courage, Trust\n|abbreviation    = DPD\n|formedyear      = 1888<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deltapolice.ca/about/history/dpdhistory.pdf |title=DPD History |access-date=2009-01-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706175013/http://deltapolice.ca/about/history/dpdhistory.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|formedmonthday  = July 7\n|employees       = 221\n|volunteers      = 180+<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deltapolice.ca/cops/cops_location.php |title=Community Police Stations |access-date=2009-01-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219161843/http://deltapolice.ca/cops/cops_location.php |archive-date=2008-12-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|budget          = 34 million CDN (2015)<ref name=stats>[http://deltapolice.ca/about/statistics/ Delta Police Statistics]</ref>\n|divtype         = Province\n|divname         = British Columbia\n|country         = Canada\n|subdivtype      = District municipality\n|subdivname      = Delta\n|governingbody   = Delta Police Board\n|constitution1   = [http://www.bclaws.ca/EPLibraries/bclaws_new/document/ID/freeside/00_96367_01#part4 BC ''Police Act'']\n|police          = Yes\n|local           = Yes\n|headquarters    = 4455 Clarence Taylor Crescent\n|stations        = {{collapsible list |title=2 |4455 Clarence Taylor Crescent |11375 84 Avenue}}\n|sworn           = 166<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deltapolice.ca/about/2008_communityreport.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-02-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205065012/http://deltapolice.ca/about/2008_communityreport.pdf |archive-date=2009-02-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|sworntype       = Police Constable\n|unsworn         = 65<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n|unsworntype     = Civilian\n|minister1name   = The Honourable [[Mike Farnworth]]\n|minister1pfo    = Minister of Public Safety and Solicitor General of British Columbia\n|minister2name   = His Worship George V. Harvie\n|minister2pfo    = Mayor & chair of the Delta [[Police board|Police Board]]\n|chief1name      = Neil Dubord\n|chief1position  = Chief Constable\n|website         = http://deltapolice.ca/\n}}\n\nThe '''Delta Police Department''' (DPD) is the police force for the City of [[Delta, British Columbia]], a suburban community in [[Metro Vancouver]] with a population of 102,661. As of 2019, the Delta Police Department has an authorized strength of 194 sworn members and 72 civilian support staff, and an operating budget of $35,981,000. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://deltapolice.ca/about-dpd/|title=About DPD|last1=Police Services|first=|date=|website=Delta Police|publisher=Delta Police Department|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Delta Police Department (DPD) became responsible for policing the [[Tsawwassen First Nation]] through an agreement between the nation and the provincial and federal government.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deltapolice.ca/tfn/index.php |title=Tsawwassen First Nation |access-date=2009-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219144114/http://deltapolice.ca/tfn/index.php |archive-date=2008-12-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Under the ''Tsawwassen First Nation Final Agreement Act'', the first nation does not have the power to establish a police force on their own, but are able to do so by requesting the minister of public safety and solicitor general. The nation chose to employ the DPD in enforcing its laws.<ref>[http://www.leg.bc.ca/38th3rd/3rd_read/gov40/gov40-3-sch-ch16.htm?toc=1 ''Tsawwassen First Nation Final Agreement Act'']</ref> {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}  \n\nIn 2020, Delta Police Department was recognized as one of BC's Top Employers 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadastop100.com/bc/|title=BC's Top Employers (2020)|last=Employers|first=BC's Top 100|website=www.canadastop100.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nDelta is one of the safest cities in the Metro Vancouver area, according to Statistics Canada Data <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surreynowleader.com/news/violent-crime-in-delta-up-overall-crime-severity-index-holds-steady/|title=Violent crime in Delta up, overall crime severity index holds steady|date=2019-07-23|website=Surrey Now-Leader|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/tbl1/en/tv.action?pid=3510006301&pickMembers%5B0%5D=1.5|title=Statistics Canada|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Crime Severity Index in Delta is just under 53 index points, as per the latest statistics from 2018.\u00a0 It continues to be significantly lower than Metro Vancouver (75.6), B.C. (88.3) and Canada (75). The Crime Severity Index not only measures the amount of crime, but also the seriousness of each offense.\n\nThe crime severity index in Delta has been declining steadily since 2014 according to Statistics Canada. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/tbl1/en/tv.action?pid=3510006301&pickMembers%5B0%5D=1.5|title=Statistics Canada|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nProperty crime in Delta trended downward in 2019, a decline of two per cent overall. Residential break and enter was down 20 per cent compared to the three-year average and theft from vehicle was down 15 per cent. The only real outlier was theft over/under $5,000, which was up 14 per cent compared to the three-year average. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Ian|first=Jacques|url=https://www.delta-optimist.com/news/from-apprehending-stabbing-suspect-to-foiling-gang-activity-delta-police-had-a-busy-2019-1.24046010|title=From Apprehending Stabbing Suspect to Foiling Gang Activity Delta Police Had a Busy 2019|date=5 January 2020|work=Delta Optimist|access-date=17 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe history of the Delta Police Department is closely tied to the first organized policing presence in British Columbia's history.\n\nIn 1858, Governor James Douglas appointed William Ladner as the first constable of New Caledonia. Ladner later went on to found the community of Ladner's Landing, which became the hub of the Municipality of Delta, British Columbia, on November 10, 1879.\n\nOn August 20, 1887, William McKee, the municipal clerk, was designated as a constable in addition to his duties as a clerk. On July 7, 1888, Joseph Jordan was appointed as Delta's first full-time constable, and with this appointment the Delta Municipal Police Department was formed. Over the next eight years Jordan was dismissed and re-appointed several times, depending on the department's needs and was assisted on occasion by other temporary constables.\n\nBy 1900, Jordan had been designated as the chief constable and worked full-time in this role until his retirement in 1911.\n\nThe chief constable's position remained the only regular full-time or part-time position until 1931, when the municipal council authorized the appointment of a night policeman. It was the duty of this policeman, whose salary was partly paid for by the local merchants, to patrol the streets of Ladner at night.\n\nThe 1950s was a decade of growth for the DPD as membership increased to 11 police officers, and the police station began operating on a 24-hour-a-day basis.\n\nBy 1971, the police department had grown to 45 police officers, due to the growth in community population after the opening of the [[George Massey Tunnel]].\n\n==Public Confidence==\nPublic confidence in Delta Police is high, according to the results of a public survey, released by police in March, 2019. Residents are confident in the Delta Police Department\u2019s ability to deliver urgent services, but want officers to be more visible in the community.\n\nRespondents thought the DPD did well in delivering urgent services in a timely manner; dealing with violent crime; having clear and transparent communication through strong social media programs; and consulting with the community to ensure the DPD is meeting their needs and expectations. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northdeltareporter.com/news/confidence-in-delta-police-high-survey/|title=Confidence in Delta police high: survey|date=2019-03-17|website=North Delta Reporter|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nSeventy-four per cent of residents give a good to very good rating of officers they had contact with, and 80 per cent of people feel the Delta Police do a good to very good job of delivering urgent services in a timely manner, well above the Canadian average. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deltapolice.ca/portfolio-items/public-confident-in-dpds-delivery-of-urgent-services-but-wants-more-police-visibility/|title=Public Confident in DPD Delivery of Urgent Services but Wants More Police Visibility|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=Delta Police|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== Recent High Profile Investigations ==\n<br />\n\n=== '''Brother\u2019s Keeper gang arrests''' ===\nIn February 2019, the DPD arrested three people associated with the Brother\u2019s Keepers gang, seizing weapons and \u201ca significant quantity of drugs.\u201d\n\nThe DPD, with the RCMP\u2019s emergency response team and members of the Combined Forces Special Enforcement Unit\u2019s uniformed gang enforcement team, executed a search warrant at a Surrey residence that had been the target of a drug trafficking investigation involving the Brother\u2019s Keepers.\n\nPolice found a loaded firearm, a replica restricted firearm and two bullet proof vests, as well as a significant quantity of suspected heroin and cocaine packaged for sale and a suspected bulk quantity of fentanyl.\n\nThree people inside the residence \u2014 two women and a man \u2014 were arrested without incident and later released, pending charge approval by Crown Counsel.\n\n\u201cTo infiltrate a gang is pretty great work by our drug detectives,\u201d Delta Police Chief Dubord said, noting the arrests highlight the inherent dangers and violence associated with drug trafficking.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surreynowleader.com/news/2019-a-year-of-successes-and-challenges-for-delta-police/|title=2019 a year of successes and challenges for Delta police|date=2020-01-09|website=Surrey Now-Leader|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n=== '''Attack on Acting Sergeant John Jasmins''' ===\nIn February 2019, Delta resident Manoj George was arrested after allegedly attacking a woman outside Immaculate Conception School in North Delta.\n\nActing Sgt. John Jasmins, who was picking up his children from school, instructed his children to call 9-1-1 and intervened in the assault, tackling the man and receiving several stab wounds to the abdomen in the process. The woman was also stabbed several times.\n\n\u201cInvestigators believe that if John hadn\u2019t acted so quickly, the woman involved in this incident could have lost her life. He is a hero,\u201d said Delta Police Chief Dubord.\n\nIn September 2019, Acting Sgt. Jasmins was awarded a Chief Constable Commendation, the DPD\u2019s highest level of recognition, for \u201chis act of exceptional courage exhibited while risking his personal safety,\u201d and in November 2019 he was presented with the Award of Valour, B.C.\u2019s highest police honour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surreynowleader.com/news/2019-a-year-of-successes-and-challenges-for-delta-police/|title=2019 a year of successes and challenges for Delta police|date=2020-01-09|website=Surrey Now-Leader|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n=== '''Project Screaming Eagle''' ===\nDelta Police arrested eight people and seized drugs, cash and a vehicle as a result of a two-month investigation into street sales of crystal methamphetamine.\n\n\u201cOur investigators recovered suspected crystal methamphetamine, cash, and evidence associated to drug trafficking at the scene,\u201d DPD public affairs manager Cris Leykauf said in a press release. \u201cWhile officers were on scene a nearby business owner came over and thanked them for their efforts, noting the residence has been problematic.\u201d\n\nThe investigation \u2014 dubbed Project Screaming Eagle \u2014 began when officers with DPD\u2019s patrol support team doing proactive patrols in the area \u201cnoticed a trend of activity consistent with drug trafficking.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northdeltareporter.com/news/delta-police-arrest-seven-seize-drugs-and-cash-from-surrey-property/|title=Delta police arrest seven, seize drugs and cash from Surrey property|date=2019-11-29|website=North Delta Reporter|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n== '''Officer Wellness \u2013 Bend Don\u2019t Break''' ==\nIn late 2018, the department launched a podcast called ''Bend, Don\u2019t Break'', which shares the stories of first responders who have overcome significant adversity in their personal and professional lives. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://podcasts.apple.com/ca/podcast/bend-dont-break/id1442139412|title=\u200eBend Don't Break on Apple Podcasts|website=Apple Podcasts|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe idea came from Const. Aaron Hill, who spoke at length in the first episode about facing an allegation of excessive force at the same time as being diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes.\n\n\"They called me and said I was being investigated for deceit\u2026 I was really concerned about what my peers would think of me,\" Hill recalled in an interview with CTV News.\n\nConst. Jordan MacWilliams is also featured in the podcast. MacWilliams was among dozens of officers called to the Starlight Casino in New Westminster for reports of a distressed man armed with a gun who had taken his ex-girlfriend hostage. In the podcast, MacWilliams describes step-by-step the actions he says officers took during that standoff, from rescuing the victim to attempts at negotiation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bc.ctvnews.ca/i-shot-him-b-c-cop-once-charged-with-murder-describes-casino-standoff-1.4259915|title='I shot him': B.C. cop once charged with murder describes casino standoff|last=Mangione|first=Kendra|date=2019-01-18|website=British Columbia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n\nListeners to the podcast <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://podcasts.apple.com/ca/podcast/bend-dont-break/id1442139412|title=\u200eBend Don't Break on Apple Podcasts|website=Apple Podcasts|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> have given it 5/5 stars. \u00a0Access to the podcast is also available on Google Play and at <nowiki>https://deltapolice.ca/podcast/</nowiki>\n<br />\n==On Duty Deaths==\nOn November 2, 1974, Staff Sergeant Ron McKay was shot and killed by Elery Long. This incident occurred when McKay attended Long's residence to speak to him regarding a confrontation that occurred earlier in the day at a local gas station. On May 27, 1975 Long was convicted of murder and sentenced to death.  On July 14, 1976, Long's death sentence, along with the death sentences of ten other people convicted of murdering peace officers, were converted to life sentences. In 2002 Long was granted full parole which has since been revoked following repeated contacts with police.\n\nOn April 8, 2000, Constable Mark Nieuwenhuis was killed in a police motorcycle accident. The investigation revealed that Nieuwenhuis was attempting to stop a vehicle at the time of the accident. A suspect has never been officially named.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Combined Forces Special Enforcement Unit of British Columbia]]\n* [[E-Comm]], 9-1-1 call and dispatch centre for Southwestern BC\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.deltapolice.ca/ Delta Police Department]\n\n{{Law enforcement agencies in Canada}}\n\n[[Category:Law enforcement agencies of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Politics of Delta, British Columbia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n|agencyname      = Delta Police Department\n|logo            = [[File:DPD Crest Small.png|DPD Crest Small]]\n|logocaption     = Badge of the Delta Police Department (DPD)\n|motto           = Honour, Integrity, Courage, Trust\n|abbreviation    = DPD\n|formedyear      = 1888<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deltapolice.ca/about/history/dpdhistory.pdf |title=DPD History |access-date=2009-01-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706175013/http://deltapolice.ca/about/history/dpdhistory.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|formedmonthday  = July 7\n|employees       = 221\n|volunteers      = 180+<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deltapolice.ca/cops/cops_location.php |title=Community Police Stations |access-date=2009-01-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219161843/http://deltapolice.ca/cops/cops_location.php |archive-date=2008-12-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|budget          = 34 million CDN (2015)<ref name=stats>[http://deltapolice.ca/about/statistics/ Delta Police Statistics]</ref>\n|divtype         = Province\n|divname         = British Columbia\n|country         = Canada\n|subdivtype      = District municipality\n|subdivname      = Delta\n|governingbody   = Delta Police Board\n|constitution1   = [http://www.bclaws.ca/EPLibraries/bclaws_new/document/ID/freeside/00_96367_01#part4 BC ''Police Act'']\n|police          = Yes\n|local           = Yes\n|headquarters    = 4455 Clarence Taylor Crescent\n|stations        = {{collapsible list |title=2 |4455 Clarence Taylor Crescent |11375 84 Avenue}}\n|sworn           = 166<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deltapolice.ca/about/2008_communityreport.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-02-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205065012/http://deltapolice.ca/about/2008_communityreport.pdf |archive-date=2009-02-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|sworntype       = Police Constable\n|unsworn         = 65<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n|unsworntype     = Civilian\n|minister1name   = The Honourable [[Mike Farnworth]]\n|minister1pfo    = Minister of Public Safety and Solicitor General of British Columbia\n|minister2name   = His Worship George V. Harvie\n|minister2pfo    = Mayor & chair of the Delta [[Police board|Police Board]]\n|chief1name      = Neil Dubord\n|chief1position  = Chief Constable\n|website         = http://deltapolice.ca/\n}}\n\nThe '''Delta Police Department''' (DPD) is the police force for the City of [[Delta, British Columbia]], a suburban community in [[Metro Vancouver]] with a population of 102,661. As of 2019, the Delta Police Department has an authorized strength of 194 sworn members and 72 civilian support staff, and an operating budget of $35,981,000. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://deltapolice.ca/about-dpd/|title=About DPD|last1=Police Services|first=|date=|website=Delta Police|publisher=Delta Police Department|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Delta Police Department (DPD) became responsible for policing the [[Tsawwassen First Nation]] through an agreement between the nation and the provincial and federal government.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deltapolice.ca/tfn/index.php |title=Tsawwassen First Nation |access-date=2009-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219144114/http://deltapolice.ca/tfn/index.php |archive-date=2008-12-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Under the ''Tsawwassen First Nation Final Agreement Act'', the first nation does not have the power to establish a police force on their own, but are able to do so by requesting the minister of public safety and solicitor general. The nation chose to employ the DPD in enforcing its laws.<ref>[http://www.leg.bc.ca/38th3rd/3rd_read/gov40/gov40-3-sch-ch16.htm?toc=1 ''Tsawwassen First Nation Final Agreement Act'']</ref> {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}  \n\nIn 2020, Delta Police Department was recognized as one of BC's Top Employers 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadastop100.com/bc/|title=BC's Top Employers (2020)|last=Employers|first=BC's Top 100|website=www.canadastop100.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nDelta is one of the safest cities in the Metro Vancouver area, according to Statistics Canada Data <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surreynowleader.com/news/violent-crime-in-delta-up-overall-crime-severity-index-holds-steady/|title=Violent crime in Delta up, overall crime severity index holds steady|date=2019-07-23|website=Surrey Now-Leader|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/tbl1/en/tv.action?pid=3510006301&pickMembers%5B0%5D=1.5|title=Statistics Canada|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Crime Severity Index in Delta is just under 53 index points, as per the latest statistics from 2018.\u00a0 It continues to be significantly lower than Metro Vancouver (75.6), B.C. (88.3) and Canada (75). The Crime Severity Index not only measures the amount of crime, but also the seriousness of each offense.\n\nThe crime severity index in Delta has been declining steadily since 2014 according to Statistics Canada. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/tbl1/en/tv.action?pid=3510006301&pickMembers%5B0%5D=1.5|title=Statistics Canada|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nProperty crime in Delta trended downward in 2019, a decline of two per cent overall. Residential break and enter was down 20 per cent compared to the three-year average and theft from vehicle was down 15 per cent. The only real outlier was theft over/under $5,000, which was up 14 per cent compared to the three-year average. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Ian|first=Jacques|url=https://www.delta-optimist.com/news/from-apprehending-stabbing-suspect-to-foiling-gang-activity-delta-police-had-a-busy-2019-1.24046010|title=From Apprehending Stabbing Suspect to Foiling Gang Activity Delta Police Had a Busy 2019|date=5 January 2020|work=Delta Optimist|access-date=17 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe history of the Delta Police Department is closely tied to the first organized policing presence in British Columbia's history.\n\nIn 1858, Governor James Douglas appointed William Ladner as the first constable of New Caledonia. Ladner later went on to found the community of Ladner's Landing, which became the hub of the Municipality of Delta, British Columbia, on November 10, 1879.\n\nOn August 20, 1887, William McKee, the municipal clerk, was designated as a constable in addition to his duties as a clerk. On July 7, 1888, Joseph Jordan was appointed as Delta's first full-time constable, and with this appointment the Delta Municipal Police Department was formed. Over the next eight years Jordan was dismissed and re-appointed several times, depending on the department's needs and was assisted on occasion by other temporary constables.\n\nBy 1900, Jordan had been designated as the chief constable and worked full-time in this role until his retirement in 1911.\n\nThe chief constable's position remained the only regular full-time or part-time position until 1931, when the municipal council authorized the appointment of a night policeman. It was the duty of this policeman, whose salary was partly paid for by the local merchants, to patrol the streets of Ladner at night.\n\nThe 1950s was a decade of growth for the DPD as membership increased to 11 police officers, and the police station began operating on a 24-hour-a-day basis.\n\nBy 1971, the police department had grown to 45 police officers, due to the growth in community population after the opening of the [[George Massey Tunnel]].\n\n==Public Confidence==\nPublic confidence in Delta Police is high, according to the results of a public survey, released by police in March, 2019. Residents are confident in the Delta Police Department\u2019s ability to deliver urgent services, but want officers to be more visible in the community.\n\nRespondents thought the DPD did well in delivering urgent services in a timely manner; dealing with violent crime; having clear and transparent communication through strong social media programs; and consulting with the community to ensure the DPD is meeting their needs and expectations. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northdeltareporter.com/news/confidence-in-delta-police-high-survey/|title=Confidence in Delta police high: survey|date=2019-03-17|website=North Delta Reporter|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nSeventy-four per cent of residents give a good to very good rating of officers they had contact with, and 80 per cent of people feel the Delta Police do a good to very good job of delivering urgent services in a timely manner, well above the Canadian average. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deltapolice.ca/portfolio-items/public-confident-in-dpds-delivery-of-urgent-services-but-wants-more-police-visibility/|title=Public Confident in DPD Delivery of Urgent Services but Wants More Police Visibility|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=Delta Police|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== Recent High Profile Investigations ==\n<br />\n\n=== '''Brother\u2019s Keeper gang arrests''' ===\nIn February 2019, the DPD arrested three people associated with the Brother\u2019s Keepers gang, seizing weapons and \u201ca significant quantity of drugs.\u201d\n\nThe DPD, with the RCMP\u2019s emergency response team and members of the Combined Forces Special Enforcement Unit\u2019s uniformed gang enforcement team, executed a search warrant at a Surrey residence that had been the target of a drug trafficking investigation involving the Brother\u2019s Keepers.\n\nPolice found a loaded fire